ing covering the face </li>\n  <li>in clear contrast to the background</li>\n  <li>without a head covering (unless it&rsquo;s worn for religious or medical reasons) </li>\n  <li>with eyes open, visible and free from reflection or glare from glasses</li>\n  <li>with your eyes not covered by sunglasses, tinted glasses, glasses frames or hair</li>\n  <li>without any shadows in the picture</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Photos for child passports</h2>\n\n<p>Children must be on their own in the picture. Babies must not be holding toys or using dummies. </p>\n\n<p>If the child is under 5, they don&rsquo;t have to be looking directly at the camera or have a neutral expression.</p>\n\n<p>If the child is under 1, their eyes don&rsquo;t have to be open. If their head is supported by a hand, the hand mustn&rsquo;t be visible in the photo.</p>\n\n<h2>Passport photos: dos and don&rsquo;ts</h2>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://assets.digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk/static/passport_photos_large.jpg\" width=\"588\" height=\"863\" alt=\"Examples of passport photos - described in text above\" /></p>\n\n","alternative_title":""},"updated_at":"2012-11-08T16:35:48+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Passports","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/citizenship%2Fpassports.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Eligibility, fees, applying, renewing and updating","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=citizenship%2Fpassports","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/citizenship/passports"},"parent":{"title":"Citizenship and life in the UK","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/citizenship.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes voting and how government works","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=citizenship","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/citizenship"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Passports and travelling abroad","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/driving%2Fpassport