ntrol?</h2>\n<p>When you arrived in the UK your passport may have been stamped. The stamp will show the terms of your stay in the UK.</p>\n\n<p>For example, your passport may have been stamped with the words &lsquo;no recourse to public funds&rsquo;.</p>\n\n<h2>When can you get tax credits?</h2>\n<p>Under certain conditions you can still get tax credits if you are subject to immigration control. </p>\n\n<h3>You have a partner</h3>\n<p>You can get tax credits if your partner lives in the UK and either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>isn&rsquo;t subject to immigration control</li>\n  <li>is one of the examples listed below</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You will still need to meet the normal <a href=\"/claim-tax-credits\" title=\"Tax credits\">tax credits</a> qualifying rules, such as the hours worked and your income.</p>\n\n<h3>You have &lsquo;no recourse to public funds&rsquo; and your money from overseas stops for a while</h3>\n<p>You may get tax credits for up to 42 days if the money you normally get from overseas stops for a short while. But it must be likely that you&rsquo;ll start getting your overseas money again soon, and you must still have permission to stay in the UK.</p>\n\n<h2>You have permission to stay in the UK - on the condition that someone else supports you</h2>\n<p>You may still be able to get tax credits if someone else is responsible for your maintenance while you are in the UK. This means that they pay for your upkeep and provide you with somewhere to live. This person is often called your &lsquo;sponsor&rsquo;, and could be a friend, employer or relative. </p>\n\n<p>All of the following must apply:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your sponsor has given the Home Office a written statement saying that they&rsquo;re sponsoring you</li>\n  <li>your sponsor has permission to stay in the UK</li>\n  <li>you&rsquo;ve been living permanently in the UK for at least 5 years, either since you came into the UK or since you started being sponsored (whichever date is later)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You may also be able to get tax credits if you&rsquo;ve been living in the UK for fewer than 5 years, but:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your sponsor has died</li>\n  <li>all your sponsors - if you had more than one - have died</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>You&rsquo;re from Algeria, Morocco, San Marino or Tunisia</h2>\n<p>You can only get <a href=\"/child-tax-credit\" title=\"Child Tax Credit\">Child Tax Credit</a>. You won&rsquo;t be able to get Working Tax Credit.</p>\n\n<h2>You&rsquo;re from Croatia or the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia</h2>\n<p>If you are a national of Croatia or the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, you may be able to get Working Tax Credit. You will need to be lawfully present in the UK.</p>\n\n<p>You can&rsquo;t normally get Child Tax Credit. However, you may be able to if you&rsquo;ve been getting payments for your children through Income Support or income-based Jobseeker&rsquo;s Allowance.</p>\n\n<h2>You&rsquo;re from Turkey</h2>\n<p>You can usually get both <a href=\"/child-tax-credit\" title=\"Child Tax Credit\">Child Tax Credit</a> and <a href=\"/working-tax-credit\" title=\"Working Tax Credit\">Working Tax Credit</a>.</p>\n\n<p>To get Working Tax Credit you need to be lawfully present in the UK and a Turkish national.</p>\n\n<h2>If you claimed asylum before 5 February 2006</h2>\n<p>You may still be able to get <a href=\"/child-tax-credit\" title=\"Child Tax Credit\">Child Tax Credit</a> if you received financial support for your children through Income Support or income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance.</p>\n"}]},"updated_at":"2012-10-22T15:12:56+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Tax credits","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/benefits%2Ftax-credits.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes Working Tax Credit, Child Tax Credit and when tax credits stop","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=benefits%2Ftax-credits","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/benefits/tax-credits"},"pare